#do all this on remote server not on main server which you want to monitor remotely from your main server 


1. Install Dependencies
AL2023 is minimal, so you'll need the development tools first:

Bash
sudo dnf install -y gcc glibc glibc-common make gettext automake autoconf openssl-devel net-snmp-devel perl-Net-SNMP
2. Install Nagios Plugins
Since nagios-plugins-all wasn't found, let's build the standard set:

Bash
cd /tmp
wget https://nagios-plugins.org/download/nagios-plugins-2.4.6.tar.gz
tar -zxvf nagios-plugins-2.4.6.tar.gz
cd nagios-plugins-2.4.6
./configure
make
sudo make install
3. Install NRPE Agent
Now, install the actual agent that will talk to your CentOS Master:

Bash
cd /tmp
wget https://github.com/NagiosEnterprises/nrpe/releases/download/nrpe-4.1.0/nrpe-4.1.0.tar.gz
tar xzf nrpe-4.1.0.tar.gz
cd nrpe-4.1.0
./configure
make all
sudo make install-groups-users
sudo make install
sudo make install-config
sudo make install-init
4. Open the Firewall (EC2 Security Group)
Since you are on an EC2 instance, you must go to the AWS Management Console:

Navigate to EC2 > Instances > Select your instance.

Go to the Security tab > Click the Security Group.

Add an Inbound Rule:

Type: Custom TCP

Port: 5666

Source: Your CentOS Master's Public IP.

5. Configure and Start NRPE
Edit the config to allow your Master IP (just like we planned for CentOS):

Bash
sudo vi /usr/local/nagios/etc/nrpe.cfg
Find allowed_hosts=127.0.0.1,::1 and add your Master IP. Then start the service:

Bash
sudo systemctl enable nrpe --now

Quick Verification
From your CentOS Master, try to "ping" this EC2 instance's NRPE:

1. Install the NRPE Plugin on your CentOS Master
You need to install the package that provides the check_nrpe binary on your local machine:

Bash
sudo yum install nagios-plugins-nrpe -y
2. Locate the Binary
After installation, verify where the file was placed. On CentOS, it usually goes into one of two places:

/usr/lib64/nagios/plugins/check_nrpe

/usr/local/nagios/libexec/check_nrpe (if you built it from source)

Run this command to find it:

Bash
find /usr -name check_nrpe
3. Create a Symlink (Optional but Recommended)
If the file is in /usr/lib64/... but you want your Nagios configuration to look in the standard /usr/local/nagios/libexec/ folder, create a symbolic link:

Bash
sudo ln -s /usr/lib64/nagios/plugins/check_nrpe /usr/local/nagios/libexec/check_nrpe
4. Run the Test Again
Now that the binary exists on your Master, try the connection again:

Bash
/usr/local/nagios/libexec/check_nrpe -H 13.203.79.4


Bash
/usr/local/nagios/libexec/check_nrpe -H <EC2_PUBLIC_IP>
